    <h1>10.2 GDPR Compliance</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <h1 id=3D"id-10.2GDPRCompliance-Prologue">Prologue</h1>
<p>The GDPR is a very large and complex part of legislature and compliance =
should ideally be reviewed by both internal and external legal advisers ski=
lled in both general privacy law and GDPR legislation. The author of this d=
ocument is&nbsp;<strong>not</strong> a lawyer or jurist and the analysis he=
reafter is purely best-effort within the provided time constraints.&nbsp;</=
p>
<h1 id=3D"id-10.2GDPRCompliance-Introduction">Introduction</h1>
<p>The General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) (EU) 2016/679 is a regulat=
ion in EU law on data protection and privacy for all individuals within the=
 European Union. It also addresses the export of personal data outside the =
EU. The GDPR aims primarily to give control to citizens and residents over =
their personal data and to simplify the regulatory environment for internat=
ional business by unifying the regulation within the EU.</p>
<p>The GDPR becomes enforceable on 25 May 2018.&nbsp;</p>
<h2 id=3D"id-10.2GDPRCompliance-WhyComply">Why Comply</h2>
<p>Fines of up to 4 million euro's or 4% of group turnover can be levied. H=
owever, these fines are more for a facebook/google/... type of "foeteren" a=
nd for most companies any penalties for not complying will be much lower.&n=
bsp;</p>
<h2 id=3D"id-10.2GDPRCompliance-PersonalInformation">Personal Information</=
h2>
<p>As the goal of the GDPR is to protect personal information, we should as=
k ourselves the question: what personal information does RAS store or handl=
e?&nbsp;</p>
<p>It turns out that the EU definition of personal information is quite bro=
ad. RAS stores the following personal information according to the EU:</p>
<ul>
<li>IP addresses</li>
<li>E-mail addresses</li>
<li>User avatars</li>
</ul>
<p>We should note, that the data transmitted by a RAS-connected asset has t=
he potential to be personal data. There should be some rule that assets may=
 not send PII to RAS.&nbsp;</p>
<h2 id=3D"id-10.2GDPRCompliance-GDPR&amp;ePrivacy">GDPR &amp; ePrivacy</h2>
<p>Privacy and Electronic Communications Directive 2002/58/EC on Privacy an=
d Electronic Communications, otherwise known as ePrivacy Directive, is an E=
U directive on data protection and privacy in the digital age. It presents =
a continuation of earlier efforts, most directly the Data Protection Direct=
ive. It deals with the regulation of a number of important issues such as c=
onfidentiality of information, treatment of traffic data, spam and cookies.=
</p>
<p>Both the GDPR and the ePrivacy directive are related, but separate direc=
tives. More about RAS &amp; ePrivacy at&nbsp;<a href=3D"/wiki/spaces/RASNEX=
/pages/83755404/10.1+ePrivacy" data-linked-resource-id=3D"83755404" data-li=
nked-resource-version=3D"1" data-linked-resource-type=3D"page">10.1 ePrivac=
y</a></p>
<h1 id=3D"id-10.2GDPRCompliance-TheGoodNews">The Good News</h1>
<h2 id=3D"id-10.2GDPRCompliance-General">General</h2>
<p><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-default">Smaller firms =E2=80=93 those =
defined as having 250 employees or less =E2=80=93 do not have to comply wit=
h all GDPR rules as standard. For smaller firms, there=E2=80=99s no need to=
 have documentation of why personal data is being collected and processed, =
the information you=E2=80=99re storing or how long for. Smaller firms are n=
ot required to maintain a record of processing activities unless this carri=
es a risk to the rights and freedoms of data subjects, it is a regular occu=
rrence, or it relates to certain data like criminal convictions and offence=
s.</span></p>
<p><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-default">In general, companies must app=
oint a DPO (data protection officer) if</span></p>
<ul>
<li>they are a public authority (except for courts acting in their judicial=
 capacity);</li>
<li>their core activities require large scale, regular and systematic monit=
oring of individuals (for example, online behavior tracking); or</li>
<li>their core activities consist of large scale processing of special cate=
gories of data or data relating to criminal convictions and offences.</li>
</ul>
<p>At this time, RAS does not meet the requirements for large scale, regula=
r and systematic monitoring and as such, the appointment of a DPO due to RA=
S is not required.&nbsp;</p>
<h2 id=3D"id-10.2GDPRCompliance-DataStorage"><span class=3D"legacy-color-te=
xt-default">Data Storage</span></h2>
<p><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-default">RAS Data is stored in Switzerl=
and, which is not a part of the EU. However, according to the GDPR, data ma=
y be stored in any country in the European Economic Area, to which Switzerl=
and does belong. Data storage is not an issue.&nbsp;</span></p>
<h1 id=3D"id-10.2GDPRCompliance-TheOtherNews"><span class=3D"legacy-color-t=
ext-default">The Other News</span></h1>
<h2 id=3D"id-10.2GDPRCompliance-PrivacyPolicy"><span class=3D"legacy-color-=
text-default">Privacy Policy</span></h2>
<p><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-default">RAS does not have a privacy po=
licy, while one is required.</span></p>
<h2 id=3D"id-10.2GDPRCompliance-Consent"><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-d=
efault">Consent</span></h2>
<p><span class=3D"legacy-color-text-default">Currently users are not requir=
ed to consent to the terms &amp; provisions. Maybe we can require users to =
give consent on first login? The whole scenario is a bit weird because user=
s don't take the first step (administrators create the accounts, so their e=
mail address is already in the database before giving consent...)</span></p=
>
<h2 id=3D"id-10.2GDPRCompliance-Reportingofdatabreaches">Reporting of data =
breaches</h2>
<p>Unlikely to happen with RAS, we'll cross that bridge when needed.&nbsp;<=
/p>
<h2 id=3D"id-10.2GDPRCompliance-AccessRequests">Access Requests</h2>
<p>Users can request a report of all PII relating to them that is stored by=
 the service. In our case, this information is very limited and once more w=
e should cross that bridge if it ever comes to it (unlikely).&nbsp;</p>
<p><br></p>
